    "The improvement in pass@1 indicates that the smaller models retain the ability to learn from the larger teacher.10K 400K 1.2M 24.2M Data set size (# of examples) 0.0 2.5 5.0 7.5 10.0 12.5 15.0 17.5 20.0 HumanEval pass@1 (%)Full FT + random init.",
    "MLFS ( =0, r=8) MLFS ( =0.9, r=8) Teacher (Santacoder 1.1B)Figure 5: Performance of MLFS on a custom Santacoder 0.7B model using 10K/400K/1.2M training examples.",
    "Data set size Model size 0.5B 0.7B 0.9B 10K 4.5 8.6 13.4 400K 4.7 9.5 13.5 Table 1: HumanEval pass@1 (%) performance of 3 small models produced by MLFS from Santacoder 1.1B.",
    "Contrary to encoder models, the compression levels that retain sufficient performance of the teacher with decoders is less.",
    "While MLFS retains accuracy performance of encoder models at 1/4 the size of the teacher, the decoder models are reduced to at most 2/3 the teacher's size.MLFS slicing of the teacher model can, however, benefit decoder models by reducing substantially the training/fine-tuning time needed compared to a randomly-initialised model, as shown in Fig. 6 on Santacoder sliced from 1.1B to 0.7B."
